{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496437"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1362"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1362"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.19,0.22,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72542"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3459"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3170"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72542"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents with a two week history of increasing discomfort in her upper abdomen. There are no other symptoms and there is no history of trauma. She had similar pain six weeks ago, but the pain was more intense and lasted about two days. On that occasion the pain was associated with vomiting. Her medical history includes an episode of acute pancreatitis two years ago, type 2 diabetes and hypertension. The only medications she takes are metformin and perindopril. She does not smoke and drinks about four glasses of wine a week. On examination there is some fullness in her left upper quadrant and this area is dull to percussion. A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pancreatic pseudocyst","Gastric outlet obstruction","Splenic haematoma","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Ascites"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA large cystic structure is visible in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. The stomach is compressed anteriorly. The coronal view shows the spleen pushed up under the diaphragm. The contents are homogeneous and of the options provided, this is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic pseudocyst\u003C/strong\u003E. The episode of pain six weeks early may well have been acute pancreatitis - from which pseudocyst formation is a well recognised complication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost patients with ascites would have a prodromal illness - something suggestive malignancy or chronic liver disease. Sometimes gastrointestinal stromal tumours can get to this size - but they usually have more of a heterogenous appearance. There is nothing from the history that would support a diagnosis of splenomegaly or splenic trauma - the latter of which would also have a heterogenous appearance. Whilst judged from the saggital view alone, this lesion could be a splenic cyst or haematoma, a normal spleen can be seen in the coronal view. Patients with gastric outlet obstruction would have symptoms of vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pancreatic pseudocyst formation is an important, but uncommon cause of upper abdominal cystic swellings."],"references":["Boxhoorn L, Voermans RP, Boewense SA, et al. Acute pancreatitis. Lancet 2020; 396:726-34. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32891214/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1362"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17877"},{"type":"media","id":"17878"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17877"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9c91b640-b289-4334-a10d-e7182fac15d2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9c91b640-b289-4334-a10d-e7182fac15d2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":532,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"17878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17878"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ec8ea93-b04b-4c72-ab17-9e9bf896680b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3ec8ea93-b04b-4c72-ab17-9e9bf896680b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":539,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T23:02:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T23:02:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72542"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T